      Status: <strong>Open Working Draft</strong><br>
      Version: <strong>1.0 · March 2026</strong><br>
      Language: <strong>EN</strong>
    </div>
    <div class="dih-status">
      <div class="dih-status-dot"></div>
      <div class="dih-status-text">Active · Subject to revision</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Nav -->
<nav>
  <a class="nav-home" href="/">aethercontinuity.org</a>
  <span class="nav-id">WP-005 · Compound Stress · Finland 2025–2035</span>
</nav>

<!-- Paper -->
<main class="paper">

  <div class="title-block">
    <div class="paper-label">Working Paper No. 005 · Domain D-1 / D-4 · Compound Stress Diagnostics</div>
    <h1 class="paper-title">Compound Stress and System Continuity:<br>Finland 2025–2035</h1>
    <p class="paper-subtitle">A diagnostic assessment of converging pressures on energy, industrial, and societal continuity in a small northern state</p>
    <div class="citation-box">
      Cite as: Aether Continuity Institute (ACI), Working Paper No. 005, 2026.<br>
      Available at: https://aethercontinuity.org/papers/wp-005<br>
      Cross-references: WP-001 (Duration Adequacy), WP-002 (DRD), WP-004 (Recovery Capacity Invariants)
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Abstract -->
  <div class="abstract-block">
    <div class="abstract-label">Abstract</div>
    <p class="abstract-text">Between 2025 and 2035, Finland's energy and societal systems will be subjected to three converging stresses that do not resolve independently: the physical progression of climate change, intensifying great-power competition over energy resources, and an unusually large wave of energy-intensive industrial investment. This paper argues that the conjunction of these three forces creates a compound stress condition that existing national planning frameworks treat as separable problems. The paper applies ACI's recovery capacity diagnostic methodology to assess the structural vulnerabilities this convergence produces. It does not advocate policy responses. It identifies the conditions under which continuity risk is structurally underestimated.</p>
    <p class="keywords">Keywords: compound stress · energy continuity · industrial investment · climate convergence · duration adequacy · recovery capacity · Finland · small-state resilience</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Section 1 -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-num">§ 01</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">Diagnostic Starting Point</h2>
    </div>
    <p>ACI's foundational claim, established in WP-001 and generalised in WP-004, is that continuity risk is not adequately characterised by capacity metrics alone. Systems fail not when capacity is absent but when the temporal structure of demand, supply, and decision capability fall out of alignment under pressure.</p>
    <p>This paper applies that diagnostic framework to a specific compound stress configuration: a small northern European state facing simultaneous pressure from climate-driven physical change, geopolitical energy competition, and an unusual concentration of capital investment in energy-intensive industry — all within a single decade.</p>
    <p>The compound character of the stress is the central analytical concern. Each of the three pressures is individually studied in existing national and European planning frameworks. What is underanalysed is their intersection: the degree to which the three stresses interact, amplify each other, and close decision windows that would remain open if the stresses were encountered sequentially.</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A system subjected to three independent stresses retains the option to manage each in turn. A system subjected to three converging stresses may exhaust its response capacity before any single one has been addressed. The distinction is not theoretical — it determines whether intervention is possible.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Section 2 -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-num">§ 02</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">The Three Stress Vectors</h2>
    </div>

    <h3 class="subsection">2.1 Climate Physical Progression</h3>
    <p>Current projections indicate that global mean temperature will likely exceed 1.5°C above pre-industrial levels on a short-term measurement basis before 2035. The multi-decadal average, the metric against which the Paris Agreement targets are assessed, currently stands at approximately 1.3–1.4°C, advancing at roughly 0.27°C per decade. For a northern state, the primary physical implications within the diagnostic window are not catastrophic but are operationally significant: increased variability in hydropower availability due to changing precipitation regimes, altered wind resource patterns, rising baseline heating demand offset by rising cooling demand, and increased exposure to weather-driven grid stress events.</p>
    <p>The more consequential climate signal for this diagnostic is geographic. As Mediterranean and North African agricultural and economic systems encounter progressive deterioration in operating conditions, the relative attractiveness of northern stable zones increases. Finland occupies a position of growing strategic interest not because its absolute conditions improve dramatically, but because its conditions deteriorate least rapidly. This asymmetry has direct implications for demographic and industrial pressure on Finnish systems beyond the planning horizon currently used in national infrastructure assessments.</p>

    <h3 class="subsection">2.2 Geopolitical Energy Competition</h3>
    <p>Europe's departure from Russian gas dependency after 2022 did not resolve its energy import vulnerability — it redistributed it across LNG from the United States, Norway, and Qatar, and transferred a growing share of technology dependency to East Asian supply chains, particularly Chinese manufacturing of solar and wind components. The strategic logic of the transition is sound; its vulnerability profile has changed rather than diminished.</p>
    <p>Finland's specific position in this landscape has a structural ambiguity. It possesses genuine competitive advantages — a northern latitude that limits solar dependency, significant wind and hydropower resources, nuclear baseload in Olkiluoto 3 — that make it an attractive host for energy-intensive industry in an era when energy cost and security of supply are increasingly decisive location factors. This attractiveness is real. It is also a source of pressure, not merely benefit, as the section below examines.</p>
    <p>At the EU level, Finland's influence over energy policy frameworks remains structurally limited. Peripheral states contribute to implementation; core states — Germany, France, and the Nordic bloc on selected issues — determine framework design. The policy environment within which Finnish energy infrastructure decisions are made is therefore substantially exogenous to Finnish decision-making. This reduces the institutional variable in the recovery capacity framework: the capacity to act is present in principle; the authority to define the framework within which action takes place is largely absent.</p>

    <h3 class="subsection">2.3 Industrial Investment Concentration</h3>
    <p>Finland is experiencing an unusually concentrated wave of energy-intensive industrial investment: battery manufacturing, data centres, green steel, electrolysis facilities, and electrifying forest industry. This investment wave is not evenly distributed over time — it is compressing into a period of roughly a decade, driven by the global transition timetable, IRA-related competitive pressure from the United States, and availability of Finnish infrastructure.</p>
    <p>The structural implication is significant. Finnish electricity consumption may plausibly double or triple by 2050. This is not a problem that can be addressed incrementally; it requires front-loaded infrastructure decisions whose consequences will constrain options for decades. The investment decisions are being made now. Their load implications materialise progressively across the 2025–2035 window and beyond.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Section 3 -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-num">§ 03</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">The Compound Stress Configuration</h2>
    </div>
    <p>The diagnostic significance of the three vectors above lies not in their individual severity but in their interaction. Three specific compound effects warrant explicit identification.</p>

    <div class="diagnostic-list">
      <div class="diagnostic-item">
        <div class="diagnostic-id">CS-1</div>
        <div class="diagnostic-text"><strong>Demand acceleration ahead of supply build-out.</strong> Industrial investment concentrates new electricity demand faster than production capacity can be constructed. The same transition that creates Finland's competitive energy advantage may produce a transient period of price spikes and adequacy stress, as the investment wave arrives before the infrastructure required to serve it. This is the duration adequacy problem identified in WP-001 in a new form: not a prolonged weather event but a structural mismatch in transition timing.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="diagnostic-item">
        <div class="diagnostic-id">CS-2</div>
        <div class="diagnostic-text"><strong>Value extraction asymmetry.</strong> Energy-intensive industry in this sector profile is capital-intensive, not labour-intensive. A battery facility or electrolysis plant at operational scale employs a fraction of the workforce per unit of capital compared to legacy industrial configurations. Furthermore, the ownership structure of these investments is predominantly foreign. Returns flow to ownership; Finland retains wages, local procurement, and tax on declared profits. The structural vulnerability here is the resource-curse analogue: a natural advantage — clean, affordable energy — is monetised primarily by external capital, while infrastructure costs and environmental externalities are borne domestically. This is not an argument against the investment; it is a diagnostic observation about the distribution of continuity benefit and continuity burden.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="diagnostic-item">
        <div class="diagnostic-id">CS-3</div>
        <div class="diagnostic-text"><strong>Temporal decision compression.</strong> The three vectors share a characteristic identified in WP-003 and WP-004: their consequences mature faster than institutional decision cycles. The political cycle is four years. Industrial infrastructure decisions lock in system configurations for thirty to fifty years. Climate physical change operates on a decadal scale. The population most exposed to the consequences of decisions made in 2025–2030 will not have voted in the elections that determine those decisions. This is not a governance failure unique to Finland. It is a structural condition of systems in which decision authority and consequence exposure are distributed across different temporal positions.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Section 4 -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-num">§ 04</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">Recovery Capacity Assessment</h2>
    </div>
    <p>Applying the three-variable diagnostic framework from WP-004 — variation, redundancy, recovery time — to the compound stress configuration above yields the following assessment. This is a structured diagnostic evaluation, not a quantitative model; its purpose is to identify trajectory rather than measure state.</p>

    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Variable</th>
            <th>Current condition</th>
            <th>Trajectory under compound stress</th>
            <th>Diagnostic signal</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Variation</td>
            <td>Moderate. Generation mix includes nuclear, wind, hydro, and CHP. Demand profile remains dominated by weather and industrial load.</td>
            <td>Declining. Investment concentration increases correlation of demand shocks. Transition toward higher share of variable renewables reduces dispatchable variation in the short term.</td>
            <td>Concern. Variation declining without offsetting redundancy build-out.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Redundancy</td>
            <td>Partially adequate. Cross-border interconnection with Sweden, Estonia (Estlink). Olkiluoto 3 provides baseload redundancy. Strategic fuel reserves maintained.</td>
            <td>Under pressure. Interconnection capacity under competing demand from multiple national transitions simultaneously. Duration adequacy of storage and dispatchable reserves insufficient for extended compound stress events (WP-001 framework).</td>
            <td>Concern trending toward Danger. Redundancy not expanding proportionally to demand growth.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Recovery time</td>
            <td>Unknown. No systematic assessment of recovery time from extended high-demand, low-generation events under the projected 2030 system configuration has been identified in public planning documents.</td>
            <td>Likely lengthening. Greater system complexity, higher dependence on non-dispatchable generation, and larger industrial loads with limited demand flexibility increase recovery time from Black Period conditions.</td>
            <td>Indeterminate — absence of measurement is itself a signal. The gap between system complexity and diagnostic coverage is growing.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>The overall gradient assessment is: recovery capacity is declining on the Concern trajectory for two of three variables and indeterminate for the third. The system is not approaching the Danger zone on any single variable. The compound stress configuration elevates concern because individual-variable assessments do not capture the interaction effects described in Section 3.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Section 5 -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-num">§ 05</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">The Societal Distribution Problem</h2>
    </div>
    <p>ACI's diagnostic scope extends to societal continuity, not only technical system continuity. The compound stress configuration generates a distribution problem that carries its own continuity risk: the benefits and burdens of the energy transition and industrial investment wave are not falling on the same populations.</p>
    <p>Industrial investment creates employment primarily for skilled labour, often requiring specialisations not locally available in the regions receiving investment. Returns flow to foreign ownership. Tax revenues, in an environment of international tax optimisation and transfer pricing, capture a fraction of the value created. Infrastructure costs — grid expansion, network fees, land use — are socialised across all electricity consumers. Environmental footprint is borne regionally.</p>
    <p>The household exposure to this asymmetry is direct and near-term: electricity prices rise as demand accelerates ahead of supply expansion. Network charges increase as infrastructure investment is recovered from consumers. These costs fall proportionally harder on lower-income households, for whom energy expenditure represents a larger share of disposable income.</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A transition that is technically well-designed but produces visible distributional asymmetry generates a political continuity risk: the erosion of the social consent required to sustain multi-decade infrastructure programmes across electoral cycles. This is not a sociological observation external to the diagnostic framework. It is a recovery capacity variable — specifically, it affects the institutional capacity to act over the time intervals that the transition requires.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Finland's historical pattern in comparable structural transitions does not provide reassurance on this point. The Nokia ecosystem's collapse produced neither effective institutional renegotiation of the terms of successor industrial arrangements nor the development of durable domestic ownership positions in successor technology chains. Mining sector foreign licensing has proceeded on terms that prioritise investment attraction over value retention. The consistent pattern is one of reactive institutional behaviour — accepting the terms offered, at speed, to secure the nominal benefit — rather than active framework-setting from a position of asset ownership.</p>
    <p>This pattern is not a failure of individual decisions. It reflects a structural feature of Finland's institutional configuration: consensus-seeking governance that functions well in stable environments performs differently in adversarial negotiation contexts, where the capacity to credibly threaten non-agreement is essential to obtaining favourable terms.</p>

    <h3 style="font-size:1.05rem;font-weight:500;margin:2rem 0 0.75rem;letter-spacing:-0.01em;">The PPA Asymmetry: Structural Displacement of Household Consumers</h3>

    <p>A specific mechanism through which distributional asymmetry is produced and locked in deserves explicit diagnostic attention. Energy-intensive industrial actors — data centres, battery manufacturing, green hydrogen facilities — routinely secure long-term Power Purchase Agreements (PPAs) directly with electricity producers, typically spanning 10–15 years at prices in the range of 30–55 €/MWh. These contracts provide price certainty, volatility protection, and in many cases priority access to newly-commissioned generation capacity that the PPA itself helped finance.</p>

    <p>Household consumers have no structural access to equivalent instruments. They are served by the retail market on spot-indexed or short-term fixed contracts, exposed to the same price volatility from which industrial counterparts have contractually shielded themselves. The irony is precise: the industrial PPA wave finances the new generation capacity that, in aggregate, should lower wholesale prices — but the capacity is pre-allocated to industrial consumers before it enters the market. The household consumer pays the spot price for capacity they cannot contract.</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>This is not a market malfunction. The PPA mechanism operates as designed. The asymmetry is structural: one class of consumer has the scale, creditworthiness, and legal capacity to contract long-term; the other does not. The market produces rational outcomes for each party individually while generating a collectively irrational distribution of risk — concentrating residual price exposure in the consumer segment least able to absorb it.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The WP-004 diagnostic framework maps this directly onto the Variation variable: the range of available hedging instruments accessible to household consumers has narrowed as the most effective instruments have been absorbed by industrial counterparties. This is not a temporary market condition. Each PPA signed locks capacity allocation for a decade or more. The structural position of household consumers in the Finnish electricity market is therefore on a declining trajectory — not because of price levels at any given moment, but because the architecture of risk allocation is becoming progressively less favourable.</p>

    <p>A further compounding factor: network charges, which are recovered from all consumers in proportion to consumption regardless of contract type, increase as industrial load growth requires grid expansion investment. The household consumer thus bears two simultaneous exposures: residual price risk on the energy component, and a proportional share of infrastructure cost driven primarily by industrial demand growth. Neither exposure is individually decisive. Their combination, sustained over the investment cycle of 2025–2035, constitutes a material deterioration in household energy affordability that operates independently of wholesale price trends.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Section 6 -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-num">§ 06</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">The Temporal Paradox in Policy</h2>
    </div>
    <p>A structural feature of the compound stress configuration deserves explicit diagnostic treatment: the temporal mismatch between the scale at which consequences manifest and the scale at which institutions are designed to respond.</p>
    <p>Energy infrastructure decisions made in the 2025–2030 window will shape system configurations through 2050–2070. Climate physical changes that are politically described as future risks are already operative within the planning horizon of infrastructure being commissioned today. Industrial investment decisions currently under negotiation will determine the electricity demand profile of the Finnish system for thirty years. Yet the institutional structures through which these decisions pass — four-year electoral cycles, annual budget processes, project-by-project permitting — are designed for a different temporal scale.</p>
    <p>This is the time paradox identified in the broader policy literature: pressure is present now; solutions are described as arriving in fifteen years; the decisions that determine which solutions become available must be made before the pressure is fully visible. The institutional consequence, observed consistently across European energy politics, is a preference for decisions that appear manageable within the current electoral cycle over decisions that are structurally correct but whose benefits materialise outside it.</p>

    <div class="definition-block">
      <div class="definition-label">Diagnostic Parallel — WP-003 ITT Framework</div>
      <div class="definition-body">The Institutional Termination Time framework developed in WP-003 identifies the point at which an institution's decision window closes with respect to a specific failure mode. The temporal structure of the compound stress configuration described in this paper exhibits ITT-adjacent characteristics: the window for low-cost intervention is open now and narrowing. Once industrial investment commitments lock in the demand profile and once infrastructure decisions reflect those commitments, the option space contracts significantly. Whether the ITT threshold has already been crossed for specific elements of Finnish energy infrastructure planning is not determinable from available public information — but the structural conditions for ITT-type closure are present.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Section 7 -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-num">§ 07</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">Diagnostic Findings</h2>
    </div>
    <p>This paper derives the following diagnostic findings. These are not policy recommendations. They are structural observations about system trajectory that are prerequisite to any subsequent technical or institutional response.</p>

    <div class="finding-list">
      <div class="finding-item">
        <div class="finding-id">Finding F-1 · Compound stress is not decomposable</div>
        <div class="finding-text">The three stress vectors — climate physical progression, geopolitical energy competition, industrial investment concentration — interact in ways that cannot be addressed by summing individual responses. Planning frameworks that treat these as separable domains will systematically underestimate the compound risk.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-item">
        <div class="finding-id">Finding F-2 · Duration adequacy gap persists under investment pressure</div>
        <div class="finding-text">The duration adequacy gap identified in WP-001 for high-electrification systems is not resolved by the investment wave; it is amplified. Greater industrial demand increases the energy integral that must be sustained across Black Period conditions. The question is not whether the gap exists but whether it is widening faster than the remediation capacity of the system.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-item">
        <div class="finding-id">Finding F-3 · Value distribution creates a secondary continuity risk</div>
        <div class="finding-text">The asymmetric distribution of transition benefits and burdens across income levels, regions, and ownership structures generates a political continuity risk that operates on the same time scale as the technical risks. Institutions that cannot sustain the social consent for multi-decade programmes face effective ITT conditions regardless of technical planning quality.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-item">
        <div class="finding-id">Finding F-4 · Negotiation posture is a structural variable</div>
        <div class="finding-text">Finland's historical pattern in comparable structural transitions suggests a systematic underperformance in capturing value from domestically-hosted, foreign-owned industrial operations. This pattern is not random; it reflects identifiable institutional characteristics. Its recurrence in the current investment wave is the expected outcome absent a deliberate structural change in negotiation posture.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-item">
        <div class="finding-id">Finding F-5 · The intervention window is open and closing</div>
        <div class="finding-text">The compound stress configuration described in this paper is in its early phase. Industrial commitments are being made; infrastructure planning is active; policy frameworks are not yet locked. This is the phase in which the recovery capacity framework (WP-004) assigns the highest diagnostic value to intervention — when trajectory correction is feasible without systemic disruption. The window is not permanently open.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-item">
        <div class="finding-id">Finding F-6 · PPA-driven capacity allocation structurally disadvantages household consumers</div>
        <div class="finding-text">The long-term Power Purchase Agreement wave accompanying industrial investment pre-allocates newly commissioned generation capacity to commercial counterparties before it enters the retail market. Household consumers retain full exposure to spot-price volatility while their access to the instruments that would hedge that exposure is structurally foreclosed. Network charge recovery further concentrates infrastructure costs on consumers who do not capture the corresponding productivity benefits. The WP-004 Variation variable for household energy consumers is on a declining trajectory that is independent of wholesale price levels.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-num">§ 08</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">Open Diagnostic Questions</h2>
    </div>
    <p>The following questions are not resolved by this paper. They are identified as the empirical and analytical priorities that would extend the diagnostic work presented here.</p>

    <div class="open-question">
      <div class="open-question-id">Q-1 · Duration adequacy under 2030–2035 load profiles</div>
      <p class="open-question-text">What is the Black Period endurance of the Finnish system under the demand profile implied by current industrial investment commitments? WP-001 established the conceptual framework; a quantitative calibration to the specific investment-augmented load scenario has not been conducted in publicly available analysis.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="open-question">
      <div class="open-question-id">Q-2 · Value capture mechanisms</div>
      <p class="open-question-text">Under what contractual and regulatory conditions have comparable small-state hosts of energy-intensive foreign investment retained materially larger shares of economic value? What structural features of those arrangements are transferable to the Finnish context?</p>
    </div>

    <div class="open-question">
      <div class="open-question-id">Q-3 · Social consent endurance</div>
      <p class="open-question-text">At what rate of electricity price increase, and at what level of distributional asymmetry, does political support for the current investment-led transition model become structurally fragile? No systematic empirical assessment of this threshold in the Finnish context has been identified in available public analysis.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="open-question">
      <div class="open-question-id">Q-4 · Interconnection adequacy under compound northern stress</div>
      <p class="open-question-text">If the compound stress configuration described in this paper affects multiple Nordic and Baltic systems simultaneously — as weather-driven events typically do — what is the effective import capacity available to Finland during a Black Period? Cross-border interconnection redundancy assessed under normal conditions may not represent available redundancy under compound regional stress.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Section 9 -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-num">§ 09</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">Relation to ACI Framework</h2>
    </div>
    <p>This paper extends the ACI diagnostic framework in two directions. It applies the duration adequacy and recovery capacity tools developed in WP-001 and WP-004 to a compound stress scenario that combines technical, geopolitical, and distributional dimensions. And it introduces the negotiation posture variable as an institutional determinant of recovery capacity — a variable not captured in the technical adequacy literature but operative in the compound stress configuration described here.</p>
    <p>The convergence with WP-004's finding is structural. Three independent analytical approaches — energy infrastructure (WP-001), defence doctrine (WP-002), institutional decision capacity (WP-003) — arrived at the same diagnostic observation: small northern states face compound stress conditions in which individual-domain adequacy assessments systematically underestimate system-level continuity risk. This paper adds a fourth domain — industrial investment and energy transition — to that convergence.</p>
    <p>Whether that convergence reflects a genuine structural feature of small-state resilience under compound stress, or reflects the selection of analytically similar cases, remains an open question. ACI's position, stated in WP-004, is that consistent convergence across independent analytical paths warrants investigation rather than dismissal.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Conclusion -->
  <div class="conclusion-block">
    <div class="conclusion-label">Diagnostic Summary</div>
    <h3>What the compound stress means</h3>
    <p>Finland in 2025–2035 is not facing a single large disruption. It is facing a configuration in which three structurally different stresses — physical climate change, geopolitical energy competition, and industrial investment concentration — converge within a single decade, interact with each other, and compress the decision windows available to institutional actors. The compound character of the configuration is what this paper has attempted to make analytically tractable.</p>
    <h3>What this diagnostic does not mean</h3>
    <p>This assessment does not claim that the compound stress configuration will produce system failure. Finland has genuine structural advantages — energy resources, institutional stability, geographic position — that provide real recovery capacity. The diagnostic finding is not that failure is likely; it is that existing planning frameworks do not fully characterise the compound risk, and that the recovery capacity trajectory is declining in the absence of deliberate intervention to reverse it.</p>
    <h3>The prior question</h3>
    <p>Before asking how to manage the compound stress, it is necessary to establish that the compound character of the stress is recognised as such. That recognition is a prerequisite for any institutional response proportionate to the actual risk. This paper aims to establish that prerequisite — and to leave the choice of response to the institutions whose responsibility it is.</p>
  </div>

